Title : Atawhai
Text : {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}
[[File:Atawhai, Nelson.jpg|thumb]]
'''Atawhai''' is one of the suburbs of [[Nelson, New Zealand]]. It lies north of Nelson and is the location of [[Wakapuaka Cemetery]], a burial place since 1861. It also has a coastline on [[Nelson Haven]] and access to [[Boulder Bank]] from [[New Zealand State Highway 6|State Highway 6]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://nelson.govt.nz/services/facilities/cemeteries/cemeteries-in-nelson-2/wakapuaka-cemetery | title=Wakapuaka Cemetery | publisher=Nelson.govt.nz | accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wonderwalkers.co.nz/default,1827,boulder-bank.sm |title=Boulder Bank |publisher=www.wonderwalkers.co.nz |accessdate=29 April 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429211952/http://www.wonderwalkers.co.nz/default%2C1827%2Cboulder-bank.sm |archivedate=29 April 2014 |df= }}</ref>

[[Nelson,_New_Zealand#Marae|Whakatū Marae]] is located in Atawhai. It is the ''[[marae]]'' (meeting ground) of [[Ngāti Kōata]], [[Ngāti Rārua]], [[Ngāti Tama ki Te Tau Ihu]], [[Ngāti Toa Rangatira]] and [[Te Atiawa o Te Waka-a-Māui]]. It includes the Kākāti ''[[wharenui]]'' (meeting house).<ref name="tkmentry">{{cite web|title=Te Kāhui Māngai directory|url= http://www.tkm.govt.nz/ |website=tkm.govt.nz|publisher=[[Te Puni Kōkiri]]}}</ref><ref name="maorimaps">{{cite web |title=Māori Maps |url=https://maorimaps.com/map |website=maorimaps.com |publisher=Te Potiki National Trust}}</ref>

